<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-721-828  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 721 828.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 2 1989 v6 n39 p92(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ABA revamps program. (Law)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schindler, Paul E., Jr.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     A.B.A. Legal Technology Advisory CouncilIllinois Institute of TechnologySoftware ValidationService Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Last month, the American Bar Association's Legal Technology Resource Centergot out of the business of testing legal software, and the Illinois Instituteof Technology (IIT) Center Software Testing Laboratory got into it.andM;The IIT's Center Software Testing Laboratory is no stranger to such work; itsseveral dozen software engineers who are based in Lanham, Md., have beentesting software for the Department of Defense for years.andM;The laboratory is new to legal software testing, however, so it will bedrawing on the resources of its Chicago-based parent organizations -- the IITChicago-Kent College of Law and the IIT Research Institute -- to find lawyersto aid in the testing process.andM;The Center Software Testing Laboratory will also have a board of advisorsappointed by the American Bar Association (ABA) to supervise its work anddraw up its testing guidelines.andM;The new program aims to offer responsive and timely service (no more thanfour months between submission of a package and completion of testing),high-quality testing (use of both software engineers and lawyer/experts),reasonable cost (vendors will still pay between $20,000 and $30,000 forcertification), up-to-date software guidelines and well-publicized results.andM;The ABA's internal testing program has come under some attack in recentyears.andM;The program attracted little fire years ago when it began testing time andbilling software.andP;  It became controversial, however, when it branched outinto other areas, such as word processing and document assembly.andM;The ABA's Legal Technology Resource Center will continue all its otherprograms to provide information and advice to attorneys on the use oftechnology in the practice of law.andM;Illinois Institute of Technology Center Software Testing Laboratory: (301)459-3711.andO;</TEXT></DOC>